In your `web.php` you have two routes that overlap.
```php
Route::get(&#39;/index&#39;, &#39;ProductController@index&#39;);
Route::get(&#39;/create&#39;, &#39;ProductController@create&#39;); 
Route::post(&#39;&#39;,&#39;ProductController@store&#39;)-&gt;name(&#39;product.store&#39;);  //&lt;----first one
Route::get(&#39;/category/index&#39;, &#39;CategoryController@index&#39;);
Route::get(&#39;/category/create&#39;, &#39;CategoryController@create&#39;);
Route::post(&#39;&#39;,&#39;CategoryController@store&#39;)-&gt;name(&#39;category.store&#39;); //&lt;----second one
```
Change the route of the second one to something else like:
```
Route::post(&#39;/category&#39;,&#39;CategoryController@store&#39;)-&gt;name(&#39;category.store&#39;);
```

The problem is your way of declaring the route name in `web.php` file. You&#39;re overriding your product storing route with category store route.

    Route::post(&#39;&#39;,&#39;ProductController@store&#39;)-&gt;name(&#39;product.store&#39;);  
    Route::post(&#39;&#39;,&#39;CategoryController@store&#39;)-&gt;name(&#39;category.store&#39;); 
For a moment you might think their route name is different, so why they are not working. The point behind not working is the route name offers some particular advantages. Let&#39;s say you want to change the route to something like &#39;product/create&#39;. Then you have to change them all over your project. If they are used 5 times, you have to change them 5times, if 50 times or more than that, I hope you can guess how much pain that would be. To get relief from that, the route name is here. Where you can give a name to route and call/refer them with their name. As a result in future if you change the route to something else you don&#39;t need to bother changing the reference as the name is still going to be the same.  But note that, ***route name*** or ***route*** can not refer or point to same **http verbs**. Here you broke the rules, Though your route name is different, you are pointing same route with same http verbs (**POST**). That&#39;s why it&#39;s overriding the previous one `Route::post(&#39;&#39;,&#39;ProductController@store&#39;)-&gt;name(&#39;product.store&#39;);` with the last one `Route::post(&#39;&#39;,&#39;CategoryController@store&#39;)-&gt;name(&#39;category.store&#39;);`. So for that route name product.store in unknown to Laravel.

*Some other minor corrections:* By default, the index file/method get fired. So you might want to replace them

    //Route::get(&#39;/&#39;, &#39;ProductController@index&#39;)
    Route::get(&#39;/index&#39;, &#39;ProductController@index&#39;);  
    //Route::get(&#39;/category&#39;, &#39;CategoryController@index&#39;)
    Route::get(&#39;/category/index&#39;, &#39;CategoryController@index&#39;);

